<title type="html"><![CDATA[I need some info about those NES assemblers.]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=10769&amp;p=122125#p122125"><![CDATA[
Well here's some problems about some assemblers.<br />I'm working on a hack project, and my source code relies on a disassembly source which should be compiled with x816.<br /><br />First to note: My source uses directives like .db instead of .byte, and uses &lt;Addr16 and &gt;Addr16 for high and lo bytes of a 16-bit value.<br />So here are results from some assemblers:<br />NESASM: Doesn't recognize &lt; and &gt;; Seems to use LSR A instead of LSR; says the symbol A is reserved.<br />x816: Runs out of memory since it operates on 16-bit DOS.<br />ca65: It doesn't recognize .db etc.<br /><br />So here's the problem:<br />1: The x816 runs out of memory on compiling a 3000-line source file. How to prevent this?<br />2: Does any other assembler use the same syntax as x816?<br /><br />Thanks.<br /><br /><br />Edit: The x816 works now, but it seems to generate syntax as SNES programs. How to generate NES programs with it?<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=5994">w7n</a> — Sun Dec 08, 2013 1:38 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
